# WispKey Proxy Routing

When constructing HTTP requests that use wisp tokens (`wk_*`), always route through the WispKey proxy.

## Proxy Address
`http://localhost:7700` (default). Set via `HTTP_PROXY` env var or pass directly.

## curl
```bash
HTTP_PROXY=http://localhost:7700 curl -H "Authorization: Bearer wk_openai_api_abc123" https://api.openai.com/v1/models
```

## Node.js / fetch
```typescript
const response = await fetch("https://api.openai.com/v1/models", {
  headers: { "Authorization": "Bearer wk_openai_api_abc123" },
  agent: new HttpsProxyAgent("http://localhost:7700")
});
```

## Python / requests
```python
import requests
response = requests.get("https://api.openai.com/v1/models",
    headers={"Authorization": "Bearer wk_openai_api_abc123"},
    proxies={"http": "http://localhost:7700", "https": "http://localhost:7700"})
```

## Docker / docker-compose
```yaml
environment:
  - HTTP_PROXY=http://host.docker.internal:7700
```

## Important
- The proxy only listens on `localhost` -- requests from other machines will not work
- Host restrictions are enforced per-credential (e.g. `openai-api` only works against `api.openai.com`)
- Every proxied request is logged in the audit trail: `wispkey log`
